<DocsLayout title="Quick Start" description="Get Engrams running in your project in under five minutes.">
  <h1>Quick Start</h1>
  <p class="lead">
    From zero to a fully-loaded project memory in five minutes.
    Make sure you have completed the <a href="/docs/installation">installation</a> first.
  </p>

  <h2>Agent Integration</h2>
  <p>
    To teach your AI agent how to interact with Engrams CLI, add these instructions to your <code>AGENTS.md</code> file, <code>.clinerules</code>, <code>.cursorrules</code>, or system prompt settings:
  </p>
  <pre><code>{`## Memory & Project Context (engrams)
You have access to the \`engrams\` CLI tool, which maintains a local SQLite database of project decisions, conventions, and progress.

1. **On Startup:** Run \`engrams activity\` to see what has changed recently. Get the \`product-context\` and \`active-context\` to orient yourself.
2. **Before Implementing:** Search \`engrams decision search "<topic>"\` and \`engrams pattern list\` to make sure your approach aligns with established decisions and codebase conventions.
3. **When making design choices:** Log them with \`engrams decision log\` so they are documented for future sessions.
4. **On Task Progress:** Track your progress using \`engrams progress log\`.
5. **On Exit:** Update the \`active-context\` to summarize where you left off for the next agent/developer.`}</code></pre>

  <h2>Interactive Walkthrough</h2>
  <div class="steps">

    <!-- Step 1 -->
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">1</div>
      <div class="step-body">
        <h3>Bootstrap from existing docs (optional)</h3>
        <p>
          If you already have a <code>README.md</code>, architecture doc, or similar, ask your AI
          to parse it and log the key facts to the Engrams database. Behind the scenes, the AI will execute CLI commands:
        </p>
        <pre><code>{`You: Parse my README.md and store our core architecture choices in Engrams.

AI:  I'll extract the core architecture choices.
     [Running: engrams decision log --summary "Use Node.js with TypeScript" --rationale "Team proficiency" ...]
     Logged 3 architectural decisions successfully!`}</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Step 2 -->
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">2</div>
      <div class="step-body">
        <h3>Log a decision manually</h3>
        <p>When you and your AI agree on a design choice, have the AI log it to keep the database fresh:</p>
        <pre><code>{`You: We've decided to use SQLite with FTS5 for local search.

AI:  Understood. Logging that decision.
     [Running: engrams decision log --summary "Use SQLite with FTS5 for local search" --rationale "Fast, local, simple" --tags "search,db"]
     Decision logged as ID 4.`}</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Step 3 -->
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">3</div>
      <div class="step-body">
        <h3>Retrieve context on demand</h3>
        <p>
          The AI agent checks Engrams at the start of a task or searches for topics to ensure it follows your conventions:
        </p>
        <pre><code>{`You: Write a search module for the database.

AI:  Let me search Engrams for search-related decisions first.
     [Running: engrams decision search "search"]
     Found:
     - Decision #4: Use SQLite with FTS5 for local search (Fast, local, simple)

     I'll implement the search module using SQLite FTS5 as decided.`}</code></pre>
        <p>
          Because the AI queried the CLI directly, it aligned with your stack choice instantly—without you needing to re-state the rules.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>

